explanation:
Why each symbol is required for analyzing possible violations of the <string.h> bounds rule:

- OS_CHECK_APINAME
  The target function calls this macro on the input timebase_name. The macro may call string functions (strlen, strncpy, strnlen, memcpy, etc.) or otherwise validate/copy the name. Its implementation is needed to determine whether it performs any unsafe string operations or enforces safe length limits.

- OS_CHECK_POINTER
  This macro validates the timer_id pointer and may produce error handling paths that affect whether timebase_name is ever used. Also its implementation can reveal whether any additional string operations (e.g., logging using the name) occur as part of the checks.

- OS_ObjectIdFindByName
  The target returns the result of this call. The implementation likely performs name comparisons or copies and is the most likely place where string.h functions are used on the provided timebase_name. Its code is essential to determine whether any string ops access beyond the provided buffer.

- OS_ObjectIdGetByName
  This is called by OS_ObjectIdFindByName (per the call graph). It is commonly the routine that iterates object entries and compares stored names to the input name (using strcmp/strncmp/memcmp or copies). Its implementation is required to inspect exact string function usage and index/buffer bounds.

- OS_ObjectIdRelease
  Called by the find/get routines; while it typically handles locking/unlocking or reference counts, including it ensures any post-processing that might copy or log names (and thus use string functions) is covered.

- OS_printf
  Used by many macros and validation paths for error reporting. If any of the above routines log or format the input name, OS_printf (or the code that prepares its arguments) may invoke string operations that could read beyond the provided string; its behavior is relevant to bound-safety analysis.

- OS_MAX_API_NAME
  The maximum name length constant (or similarly named constant) is typically used by checks and in object record name buffer sizes. Knowing its value and usage is necessary to determine if copies/compares are bounded correctly and if stored name buffers are large enough for the operations performed.

- OS_object_record_t (or the object record struct that stores object names)
  The structure definition that contains the stored name field (and its declared size) is required to check whether routines copy the input name into that field safely and whether comparisons reference valid memory ranges.

- OS_object_table (or the global object table / array used by ObjectIdFindByName)
  The concrete data structure iterated by the find/get routines is needed to see how name fields are accessed, whether any indexing could lead to out-of-bounds reads/writes when string functions are used, and to confirm the stored name buffer sizes and lifetime.

These symbols together cover the macros that validate the incoming name, the routines that search/compare/copy names, the object storage that holds names (and their declared bounds), and the logging path. Inspecting their implementations and the OS_MAX_API_NAME constant is sufficient to determine whether any use of <string.h> functions can read or write beyond the bounds of the provided objects in the context of OS_TimeBaseGetIdByName.
